five sample summaries

[1]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[2] Takaharu Tezuka designed the circle kindergarten with no roof in the middle and boundaries in 2007. He designed it because children like to make a circle to walk and run. There are a lot of trees popping through, and children play with them. They can live with naitures in this kindergarten. The time of the event, they sit on the edge of the building. They can see the ground even if they are sitting because the roof is made so high. This kindergarten is complementary open most of the year. He has the question why you put many children in the square box, so he did not make boundaries between classrooms to remove the barrier. When children are sleeping, he said we should not make quiet places. He also introduced a second building which is five metres tall. They can learn how they help each other because of this design. His point is do not control them and protect them too much, and they need to be tackled sometimes.                                            
[3] In his TED Talk, architect Takaharu Tezuka introduces Fuji Kindergarten in Tokyo, designed to support children’s freedom and natural development. The school features a circular building with a rooftop playground, where children can run freely—about 4 kilometers every morning. There are no walls between classrooms, creating an open, flexible environment that reduces stress and encourages movement. Tezuka believes children thrive in environments where they can hear sounds, see nature, and move freely. Trees grow through the building, and nets on the rooftop allow safe climbing. He also emphasizes the importance of letting children take risks, saying that falling is part of growing up. The design encourages social interaction, creativity, and resilience, making learning part of everyday life. Tezuka concludes that architecture can change education by creating spaces that truly match children’s needs. His kindergarten offers a new vision of what school can be.
[4] There is a circular kindergarten. The roof of the kindergarten is low because the children on the rooftop can be seen. There are also other ingenious designs such as washing areas of various shapes. The kindergarten is completely open all year round, meaning there are no barriers between classrooms. Confining a large number of children to a quiet area can make some of them restless. Second, noise is very important. Children can sleep better in a noisy environment, and they can have amazing concentration in a class. These days, people want to control everything. This kindergarten safety must be considered. However, children also need a little danger. In these places they learn to help each other. The important thing is not to control them, not to overprotect them, and that they have injuries sometimes. They are there to learn how to live in the world. Architecture is one aspect that supports children’s lives.                                                 
[5] This kindergarten was built in 2007. The building is circular. We had planned not to install handrails, but the government said that it wouldn't be approved unless handrails were installed. So we installed many trees on the roof and spread nets around them. Children will fall onto them intentionally. This leads to a more relaxed lifestyle for the children. The roof is designed to be low so that students can see the children. Also, there are no walls between classrooms, so it is good that students can see the children. When they play on the playground equipment, they learn that in this society, we cannot survive without helping each other . They run around on the roof, but we must not overprotect their children. Sometimes they get hurt, which teaches them how to survive in this society and how difficult it is.
